releases/0/tender/title: Call-Off Cost Assessment Technical Support for Mergers
releases/0/tender/description:
Objective(s)

This call-off contract will:

•	Provide Ofwat with technical support on cost assessment at relatively short notice. This will include technical assessment of company proposals, including the effect on our ability to use comparators and the impact of reducing the number of comparators;

•	Provide Ofwat with advice and support in preparing merger impact assessments; and

•	Provide Ofwat with technical advice in responding to any CMA process including attending hearings or meetings.

Scope

This would be a call-off contract for the period up to 31 March 2017. The scope of this work is limited to:

•	Technical assessment of company proposals, including the effects on our ability to use comparators;
•	Technical assessment of the impact of reducing the number of comparators;
•	Advice and support in preparing merger impact assessments;
•	Technical advice in responding to any CMA process, including attending hearings or meetings; and 
•	Drafting and correspondence relating to any CMA or pre-referral process.

We would expect bidders to specify a call-off notice period and day-rate as part of their tender. 

Ofwat reserves the right to award the work to more than one Supplier.

Key Tasks

This work will be ad hoc (known as the “Activity”) when the need arises within the scope. We would expect a successful bidder to have availability for a few days at the beginning of the contract for initial meetings with Ofwat staff and familiarisation with the material.
There are no fixed deliverables for the Activity. Timescales for the completion of the Activity will be agreed with the Ofwat Project Manager.

Additional information: Please note that this is a call-off contract so it is difficult to quantify  exact spend.

For further information, please contact:  procurement@ofwat.gsi.gov.uk

releases/0/tender/title: Non-Household Customer Research into Retail Competition Awareness
releases/0/tender/description:
Objectives of the work
A strong factor for market success, and for the benefits to be delivered, is customer awareness. If customers are sufficiently aware of, and engage with, the opening of the retail market then they can promote effective competition by being actively involved in managing their water retail services. 

The research needs to provide the programme with a clear baseline for the current levels of non-household (business, charities and public sector) customers’ awareness. This should include their understanding of the forthcoming ability to switch supplier and perceived or actual barriers to switching. The research findings will then enable the programme to implement appropriately targeted communications and engagement activities to increase awareness. It will also give us a baseline for post market opening monitoring.

Key Outputs and Deliverables
The Provider is required to deliver the following key outputs:
•	An agreed programme for the research (including scope and timelines)
•	All raw survey data in an agreed format
•	Draft and final reports on questionnaire results
•	Draft and final reports on initial findings, analysis and recommendations from the questionnaire
•	Draft and final detailed report on findings, analysis and recommendations from the focus groups

Timescales
To ensure that effective action can be taken before the market opens, the research needs to be completed by 18 November 2016 with a service start date of 19 September 2016 or earlier. We would expect to see emerging results as and when they are available. We appreciate that both phases of the research may need to happen in parallel to meet this deadline.

releases/0/tender/title: Cultural Citizens Programme Evaluation
releases/0/tender/description:
The Cultural Citizens Programme was included in the Culture White Paper as an effort to ensure that every child has culture as part of their education both in and out of school. The programme targets disadvantaged communities where fewer people currently visit museums, galleries or the theatre.  It will be initially piloted in three areas and, if successful aims to be rolled out to thousands of young people across the country.

Arts Council England has been tasked by the Department of Culture Media and Sport (DCMS) to deliver the Cultural Citizens Programme Pilot. The programme has now launched and the delivery partners are in the process of identifying the participants. 

Arts Council England is seeking a service provider to deliver an evaluation of the Programme.The evaluation needs to assess whether the programme has been successful in its aims and whether a future expansion of the programme would be a worthwhile endeavour.

 The provider will need to quickly engage with the delivery partners and come to an understanding of how the evaluation programme will fit around each pilot as they are delivered over the 2016-17 school year.

releases/0/tender/title: Technical Review Support for the completion of the Hitachi-GE UK ABWR C&I GDA Step 4
releases/0/tender/description:
ONR is seeking to engage one of the Technical Support Contractors (TSCs) appointed to Lot 6 of its technical support framework agreement for the majority of Step 4.  At present, it is anticipated that the engagement will last until autumn 2017 with the drafting of Step 4 Assessment Report. 

The TSC resource engaged will be directed by, and work with, ONR’s GDA C&I assessment team. For efficiency it is expected that they will primarily communicate with ONR C&I staff by teleconference and attending meetings at ONR’s Redgrave Court office in Bootle. However ONR would be prepared to consider flexible location arrangements to accommodate efficiency savings. Attendance at meetings in Japan and other areas in the UK will be required, as needed.

The required resource is two full time equivalent (FTE) professional engineering personnel. Where more than two persons are necessary to provide this resource (e.g. part-time staff), then it is essential that measures are provided to ensure adequate cooperation and coordination between individuals. The main area of work will be the review of C&I safety case documentation and the supporting technical submissions, reporting on findings, and contributing to technical meetings in both the UK and Japan.

ONR is looking for experienced personnel with knowledge of nuclear reactor C&I safety cases to review both Hitachi-GE’s submissions and any independent confirmatory analysis commissioned by ONR. Activities to be delivered as part of this work will include but not be limited to:
•	Review Hitachi-GE’s C&I submissions against ONR’s SAPs, ONR’s technical assessment guides, relevant international standards, and UK/international relevant good practice. 
•	Support ONR (including any required preparation) during teleconferences, videoconferences and / or face-to-face meetings (in the UK and Japan) with Hitachi-GE to discuss progress of the reviews of the various related tasks, findings from the reviews, emerging issues, etc, and / or to request additional information and / or analysis from Hitachi-GE.
•	Draft requests for additional information and / or analysis from Hitachi-GE and advise ONR on the adequacy of the responses.	
•	Provide C&I progress updates to internal ONR meetings where necessary.
•	Assist in the authoring of the Step 4 control and instrumentation Assessment Report, capturing ONR’s assessment of Hitachi-GE submissions and responses to technical questions

releases/0/tender/title: Provision of Total Media and Social Media Requirement
releases/0/tender/description:
Arden & GEM is one of the largest Commissioning Support Units in the country. Our customers include more than 60 Clinical Commissioning Groups (CCG), NHS England, local authorities and a range of care providers.
With offices throughout the Midlands, North West and South East we cover a core geographic patch that extends to Greater Manchester in the north and Essex in the south. Our services are built on a strong foundation of experienced people who build great relationships, a commitment to NHS values and a thorough understanding of our clients and the challenges they face.
We provide real value to our customers by working at scale, creating the synergies and innovation that ultimately drives improved patient outcomes and makes commissioning resources work harder.
Our cornerstones are quality, value, innovation and complete customer focus.
We are a ‘one-stop shop’ for commissioners. Drawing from our extensive experience, our services bring local knowledge and relationships whilst offering the benefits of operating at scale and sharing best practice.
Arden and GEM Commissioning Support Unit:
•	Emphasises excellence and high performance
•	Provides value for money
•	Adds regional strength to local relationships
•	Offers a synergy of NHS core values and commercial enterprise
•	Embeds innovation and transformation - a need to work differently to succeed
•	Develops new career and personal development opportunities for staff

NHS Arden & GEM CSU provides high quality services for citizens.  We deliver commissioning support, business support and clinical support services to over 60 CCGs, NHS England, local authorities and care providers. We focus on exceptional local delivery while operating at scale to provide value and share innovation.
NHS Arden & GEM CSU’s engagement, communications and social marketing team have extensive experience working in and with public and private sector health and social care organisations and share your passion to transform people’s lives through better care. The long term health and wellbeing of our citizens continues to be a key driver for clinical commissioning decisions. As experts in social marketing, we also devise and run engagement campaigns to effect attitude, whether to encourage healthier lifestyles or to change perceptions about how individuals access services.
A key service category is Communications and Engagement and the provision of a first class media relations service which is customer focused and highly responsive. Effective media monitoring will provide a true benchmark of our success. The service will enable us to respond swiftly and take control of media issues to enhance our customers’ reputations. It’s about being equipped to overcome every challenge and seize every opportunity.

releases/0/tender/title: Horsham District Council - Conservation Area Reviews and Managment Plans Invitation to Quote
releases/0/tender/description:
Horsham District is located in West Sussex, within the South East of England.  The district is predominantly rural in character, and contains a number of small villages and towns. The largest urban area is the market town of Horsham, situated in the north east of the District.  Horsham District is an appealing place to live, work and visit.  The towns and villages in the District are very attractive, with many historic buildings.  The character of the settlements varies across the District, and each has a unique identity, with different sizes, building types and relationship with the surrounding landscape.  There are a range of building materials seen across the District from tile hanging and flint as well as the particularly distinctive Horsham Stone which is used as a roofing material in a number of towns and villages in the District. 

A full review of the Conservation Areas within Horsham District (except the area within the South Downs National Park) should be undertaken to enable the protection of these areas, which should include appraisals assessing the character of each Conservation Area. The approach to the conservation areas should start afresh, reviewing the current area boundaries and reassessing the areas and identifying the positive and negative elements for inclusion or ‘removal’.  Proposals for the future management of the Conservation Areas should be thoroughly researched, so that these can be consulted upon and adopted by Horsham District Council.

Additional information: This quotation is to be completed electronically using the SE Shared Services Procurement eSourcing portal.

https://www.sesharedservices.org.uk/esourcing/opportunities

The SE Shared Services eSourcing portal provides a web-based tool that provides a simple, secure and efficient means for managing tendering and quotation activities reducing the time and effort required for both buyers and Potential Bidders. The portal allows for clarifications and submitting your bid electronically. 

In order to bid for this opportunity you will need to register your company on the SE Shared Services portal.

releases/0/tender/title: CP1297-16(2) Transportation of Bodies on behalf of Her Majesty’s Coroner for North Devon, West Devon and Torridge
releases/0/tender/description: In certain cases, when there is a sudden death it is the responsibility of the Coroner to examine the cause of death. This may result in a post mortem examination being carried out. It is also the Coroner’s responsibility to remove bodies from the scene of death to the Mortuary, pending investigation into the death. Cases that require body removal are mainly limited to community deaths as opposed to hospital deaths. All deaths in relation to which no Doctor is able to sign a certificate have to be referred to the Coroner. The Coroner, Coroner’s Officer or a Police Officer will instruct an undertaker to collect the body and take it to the Mortuary. This Framework Agreement is to be awarded to allow the efficient, timely and professional removal of bodies to the Coroner’s chosen destination, both within the Exeter and Greater Devon and may also include when required long distance transfers within the UK.

releases/0/tender/title: Provision of Support on the Review of PSR3 related to C & I Ageing and Obsolescence
releases/0/tender/description:
Under LC 15, ONR is required to approve the PSR3 submissions, in this case for Hinkley Point B and Hunterston B Power Stations. This approval therefore requires ONR technical assessors in all the relevant disciples to review the submission against relevant good and best practice, ONR SAPS and TAGs and national and international standards.

This project is to support ONR in undertaking the Control and Instrumentation (C&I) review of the PSR3 submissions in the area of ageing and obsolescence.

The ONR require technical expertise to be provided with prior knowledge and experience of national and international standards including good and best practice related to C&I ageing and obsolescence. 
The task can be broken down into three main areas:-
	Task 1 – Outline the National and International Standards and good and best practice for C&I Ageing and Obsolescence 
	This is an overview covering all the relevant C&I Ageing and Obsolescence standards and practice.
	Task 2 – Review of PSR3 Documents
	This task it to assess the following document PSR3 documents against the standards and practices outlined in task 1.
•	PSR3 Codes and standards review Appendix B (9 pages)
•	Ageing and lifetime management Appendix C (7 pages)
		The purpose of the review will be to assess if all relevant national and international standards and good and best practice has been considered within the PSR3 documents referenced above.
Task 3 – Description of any gaps
If there are any gaps found then the final report should briefly outline the standard or practice which has not been included and how this could have impacted the PSR3 document.

releases/0/tender/title: Europeana Sounds Project Independent Evaluation
releases/0/tender/description:
Europeana Sounds is a three year EC-funded project running between January 2014 and January 2017. 

The key objective of the project has been to open a gateway to Europe’s sound and music heritage and to increase its accessibility. In order to meet this objective, work was planned at the start of the project to:
●	Increase the amount of audio content available via Europeana and improve geographical and thematic coverage by aggregating recordings with widespread popular appeal
●	Improve their access by enriching descriptions, developing techniques for cross-media and cross-collection linking
●	Develop audience-specific sound channels that will improve search facility, navigation and user experience
●	Promote the creative reuse of recordings
●	Identify and advocate recommendations on how to resolve domain constraints and improve access to out of commerce audio content, working with music publishers and rights holders
●	Build a network of stakeholders: specialists in technology, rights issues, software development and sound archives. The network will expand to new content-providers and mainstream distribution platforms to ensure the widest possible availability.

The activities of the project are organised within seven thematic work packages: aggregation, enrichment & participation, licensing guidelines, channels development, technical infrastructure, dissemination & networking and project management. 

The project is now nearing the end of its three year lifetime and the project management team would like to commission  an independent evaluation that needs to discover which areas the project has been successful in and where improvements could be made. This evaluation will be shared in confidence solely with the project consortium. Its findings will feed into a final evaluation report to be written by the project management team in December 2016. 

If you are interested in participating in this tender please go to the British Library’s e-tendering portal at https://bl.bravosolution.co.uk, click on ‘View current opportunities and notices' link on the Home page and follow the on screen instructions in regards to registration and downloading the tender documents.

releases/0/tender/title: WCC - Emotional well-being and mental health services for children and young people aged 0-25 in Warwickshire
releases/0/tender/description:
Warwickshire County Council together with NHS Warwickshire North Clinical Commissioning Group, NHS Coventry and Rugby Clinical Commissioning Group and NHS South Warwickshire Clinical Commissioning Group (the “Commissioners”) are inviting providers to participate in a competitive dialogue process with the aim of awarding a contract for the Emotional well-being and mental health services for children and young people aged 0-25 in Warwickshire.
The Commissioners are seeking a high quality, safe and affordable solution that promotes prevention, early intervention, building resilience and works in an integrated way with other service areas and families.

WCC is acting as lead commissioner in this process.
These Services may be subject to modifications and changes in order to meet the changing needs and demands of the Council, the CCG’s and the customers. This may also be as the result of additional funding streams and new initiatives. Further details are included in the tender documents.

We are seeking proposals for a service delivery model that will provide a whole emotional well-being and mental health system for 0-25 yr olds within a single contracting solution (either a Prime Contractor or Formal Alliance model).
The procurement process will follow a competitive dialogue process with the aim of enabling the applicants and the Commissioners to combine their knowledge and expertise to develop a solution that can meet the needs of the children and young people of Warwickshire.
This contract may be used to commission any other children’s health/ care services in the future which may include but not limited to: All age neurodevelopmental assessment; Community eating disorder; Speech and language therapy; Physiotherapy; Occupational Therapy; School nursing; Health visiting; Family nurse partnership; Troubled families; Any other children’s health or care service.
Providers will need to demonstrate how their service provision will integrate with existing providers

Applicants should be aware that on award of new contracts, it is possible that the Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) Regulations 2006 may apply.
The initial contract term will be 5 years however the Council reserves the right to extend the contract by further periods not exceeding 24 months.
The 0-17yr old budget is approx £5.5m pa.(18-25yr old is TBA during the process)

Coventry City Council and NHS Coventry and Rugby CCG are commissioning a different service provision for the Coventry area. However it is possible that in the future they could commission those services from the contract(s) awarded through this tender process.



Additional information: Warwickshire County Council will be using its e-tendering system (CSW-JETS) for the administration of this procurement process. Providers must register with the system (if they haven’t previously done so) in order to be able to express an interest in the project and download documents. The web address for CSW-JETS is www.csw-jets.co.uk

Registration and use of CSW-JETS is free.

If you are having trouble registering with CSW-JETS  please email us at procurement@warwickshire.gov.uk


Is a Recurrent Procurement Type? : No https://in-tendhost.co.uk/csw-jets/aspx/

releases/0/tender/title: Minor Roads Surfacing Contract 2016/17 - AWARD
releases/0/tender/description:
Reading Borough Council is seeking an experienced contractor to enter into a contract with to carry out surfacing works on various areas of carriageway within the Highway Network as part of the Council’s annual highways maintenance programme.

The areas have been selected by a scanner process and routine visual inspections.

A core programme of works has been identified, along with a further list of reserve schemes that may be completed by the successful contractor, subject to funding.

The Contractor will be required to undertake the following main elements of work: -

• Weed killing in advance of the works
• Removal of road markings as required by the process.
• Sweeping of carriageway, removal of vegetation and preparing to lay surfacing.
• Laying of Micro Asphalt or equivalent proprietary surfacing material including regulating.
• Jetting and cleaning of gullies.
• Raising existing ironwork to new levels.
• Reinstatement of existing road markings with minor alterations as specified by the Council.
• Management of pedestrian and vehicular traffic including road closures with diversion routes.

The contract value is expected to be in the region of £120k - £220k

releases/0/title: Mount and Bishop Court Flats Re Cladding- CONSTRUCTION WORK
releases/0/planning/documents/0/descript: Early engagement notice on Contracts Finder
releases/0/tender/title: Mount and Bishop Court Flats Re Cladding- CONSTRUCTION WORK
releases/0/tender/description:
Guildford Borough Council wishes to undertake soft market testing before inviting tenders for recladding two adjacent high-rise blocks of flats, Mount Court and Bishop Court, in central Guildford.
Areas which the Council would like to discuss with potential suppliers include the contracting/ procurement route and aspects which would increase market interest and avoid excessive risk- based pricing

We would like to ask supplers, who have experience in this field, what is the most suitable procurement route. The Council wishes to talk to firms to help identify if two stage or single stage Design and Build is the most advantageous procurement route for the Council. In addition we would like to provide information on the forthcoming procurement to build market interest and to garner the views of expert suppliers as to generally the best way to proceed. The Council would like to validate that it has provided or will provide sufficient information to bidders to prevent excessive risk- based pricing. We also wish to consider issues which would assist the client’s team to approach the project works in the most effective manner, having regard to how design and procurement will integrate with the town and country planning process.

Please send your 1000 to 2000 word written submission to David.Budd@guildford.gov.uk by 18 October 2016.
